            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "By developing on the same setup you're deploying to, you're more likely not to clearly separate hacks for a specific setup from the actual application. Especially for a high-level language such as python it is rather unlikely for trivial issues to occur on one specific platform only. This is why the builtin dev server suffices IMO. Remaining platform-specific failures usually can be analyzed with Sentry or at least proper logging.\n\n> ```\n> if __name__ == '__main__':\n>     application.run(debug=True)\n> ```\n> \n> ... however this will not work with mod_wsgi, now I know.\n\nIn my opinion it is not neccessary for a particular part of the documentation to reiterate the most basic of basics covered both in the [Quickstart](http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/quickstart/#quickstart):\n\n> So what did that code do? [...] Finally we use the run() function to run the **_local server**_ with our application.\n\n... and the [documentation for `app.run`](http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/api/#flask.Flask.run):\n\n> **_local development server**_\n\n... just to compensate for the short attention span of the reader.\n"
        },
